`crates/steno/` is the `steno` theory-compiler library plus the binaries and tests that consume it. The library (`src/`) turns fenced `.steno` source into Plover dictionaries, LSP snippets, and `@literal` keystroke sequences through a strictly staged, no-panic pipeline; everything else in the crate — the four binaries and the entire test suite — depends only on `lib.rs`'s re-exports, so a renamed export or a changed pipeline stage ripples everywhere at once.

The crate's actual behavioral contract lives more in `tests/` than in the library's own doc comments: indent widths, auto-close sets, error-message substrings, sentinel formats, and chunk grammar are pinned by test assertions, not by prose. Both subtrees share a load-bearing dependency on the repo-root `dict.steno` corpus — the library's pipeline processes it as ordinary input, but nine of eleven test files hardcode specific stroke names and corpus-wide counts against it, so any edit to `dict.steno` must be paired with a look at those tests (lookup panics there, not assertion failures, are the usual symptom of drift). The two subtrees also independently encode the same terminal/non-terminal classification rule for strokes — `render/`/`snippet/` implement it, `snippet.rs`'s prefix-collision test and `nvim_plugin.rs`'s behavioral dependency both guard it from the outside — so a classification bug can pass compilation and still be caught only by the test side.

A cross-cutting change to `parse/mod.rs`, `expand/mod.rs`, or `editor/mod.rs` (new AST variant, pipeline pass, or `Event`/`Behaviors` field) ripples through every downstream `src/` stage *and* typically requires updating multiple test files in lockstep, since tests hand-construct `TypedEntry`s and parse fixtures tied to the current shape of those types.